# Topic 75: Partitioning ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

## Why?

Suppose

```text
100 Million Records
```

One executor processes everything.

Other executors remain idle.

Very slow.

---

## Concept

**Partitioning** divides data into multiple partitions so Spark can process them in parallel.

> **Simple Definition:** Split data into smaller pieces for parallel processing.

---

## Theory

Without Partitioning

```text
100 Million Records

↓

Executor 1
```

---

With Partitioning

```text
Partition 1 → Executor 1

Partition 2 → Executor 2

Partition 3 → Executor 3

Partition 4 → Executor 4
```

All executors work simultaneously.

---

## Architecture

```text
Large Dataset
      │
      ▼
Partitions
 │   │   │   │
 ▼   ▼   ▼   ▼
E1  E2  E3  E4
```

---

## Syntax

```python
df = df.repartition(8)
```

---

## Types

### Hash Partitioning

Based on column values.

Example

```python
df.repartition("customer_id")
```

---

### Range Partitioning

Based on value ranges.

Useful for ordered data.

---

## Real-world Example

Sales Table

```
500 Million Rows
```

Partition by

```
Country
```

Now

India

USA

UK

Australia

can process independently.

---

## Interview Questions

### What is Partitioning?

Splitting data into smaller partitions for parallel processing.

---

### Why is Partitioning important?

Improves parallelism and reduces execution time.

---

### Does Partitioning improve every query?

No.

Incorrect partitioning can increase shuffle and reduce performance.

---

## ETL Usage

Large ETL

↓

Partition Data

↓

Parallel Processing

↓

Faster Pipeline

---

## Common Mistakes

❌ Creating too many partitions (too much scheduling overhead).

❌ Creating too few partitions (poor parallelism).

❌ Partitioning by a low-cardinality column without considering data distribution (can create imbalance).

---

# ⭐ Broadcast Join vs Partitioning

| Broadcast Join               | Partitioning                      |
| ---------------------------- | --------------------------------- |
| Join optimization            | Data distribution strategy        |
| Used during joins            | Used before/throughout processing |
| Small table copied           | Large dataset divided             |
| Reduces shuffle during joins | Improves parallel processing      |

---

# ⭐ Interview Cheat Sheet

| Topic          | One-line Answer                                                            |
| -------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Broadcast Join | Send the small table to every executor to avoid shuffling the large table. |
| Partitioning   | Split data into partitions for parallel processing.                        |

